const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why does my Samsung dryer keep blowing the thermal fuse?",
    a: "Thermal fuse failure is the single most common Samsung dryer problem we see, and the answer is almost never \"the fuse is bad\" by itself. The thermal fuse is a one-time safety device that blows when the dryer overheats, its job is to prevent a fire. The overheat is the actual problem, and 90% of the time it's caused by a partially blocked vent run (lint accumulation in the duct, crushed flexible ducting behind the dryer, or a clogged exterior wall cap). Replacing the fuse without clearing the vent means the new fuse will blow within weeks. Less common causes of repeat thermal-fuse failure: failing cycling thermostat (the primary safety thermostat that should have tripped first), bad heating element shorting to ground, or a failing thermistor giving the control board bad temperature readings. Our techs always inspect the full vent run from the dryer back to the exterior wall cap before replacing a thermal fuse. The fuse alone is a $145-$245 repair; the right job, vent cleaning + fuse replacement, is the same call and prevents the next failure."
  },
  {
    q: "What does a tE error mean on my Samsung dryer?",
    a: "tE on a Samsung dryer is a temperature-sensor (thermistor) fault, the control board has lost a valid temperature reading from one of the thermistors that monitor exhaust temperature, drum temperature, or heater temperature. Three diagnostic outcomes: (1) Open or shorted thermistor, the sensor itself has failed, replacement runs $145-$215. (2) Harness fault, wire from thermistor to control board has chafed or disconnected, repair runs $125-$185. (3) Control board fault, less common but possible, the board is reading the thermistor incorrectly, $345-$525 to replace. Diagnostic order: full reset (unplug 30 seconds or hold Start/Pause 5 seconds). About 10% of tE codes clear at this step, a transient sensor read that the board latched. If tE returns immediately, the diagnostic separates thermistor / harness / board with multimeter testing in 15-20 minutes on-site."
  },
  {
    q: "What does an HE error mean on my Samsung dryer?",
    a: "HE on a Samsung dryer is a heating error, the dryer's exhaust temperature exceeded the safe limit, OR the heater isn't producing heat when commanded. The HE code can mean two opposite things depending on the failure mode: overheating (vent restriction, stuck heating contactor) or no-heat (heating element burnout, blown thermal fuse, gas valve coil failure on gas models). Diagnostic order: (1) Always inspect the vent first, clogged vent is the cause majority of the time on the overheating side of HE. (2) If vent is clear and dryer isn't heating, test the heating element with multimeter (electric models) or the gas valve coils (gas models). (3) If element/coil tests fine, check thermal fuse and cycling thermostat. (4) Last suspect: control board commanding the heater incorrectly. About 60% of HE codes resolve at vent + thermal fuse; 30% at heating element; 10% at thermostat or board."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does it cost to repair a Samsung dryer?",
    a: "Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when work is approved. Common Samsung dryer repairs at our typical pricing: thermal fuse + vent inspection $145-$245; heating element replacement (electric) $285-$425; gas valve coil replacement (gas) $245-$385; thermistor replacement $145-$215; cycling thermostat replacement $145-$215; door switch / latch $145-$215; drum belt + idler pulley $195-$295 (the squeaking-dryer fix on most calls); drum support roller (front + rear bearings) $245-$385; drive motor $385-$580; main control board $345-$525. Premium model uplift on Samsung dryers (DV-FlexDry, DV-WashTower vertical stack, MultiSteam variants): 15-20% above the standard band. Most Samsung dryer repairs land in the $145-$425 range. If your repair quote crosses $500-$600 on a dryer over 8 years old, we'll tell you the repair-vs-replace math honestly, sometimes the right move is replacement, and we say so."
  },
  {
    q: "When should I replace my Samsung dryer instead of repairing it?",
    a: "Honest framework. Under year 6, repair almost always, Samsung dryers should run reliably to year 12-15 with vent maintenance, and a repair under year 6 buys 6+ years of additional service. Year 6-10 with the typical thermal fuse + vent + element work, repair is still the right call for most repairs under $400. Year 10-12 with major repair (drive motor, control board, multiple components): repair-vs-replace tilts toward replacement, especially if the dryer is one of the entry-tier DV2 series. Year 12+: replacement is usually right unless you have a high-spec FlexDry or WashTower where the replacement cost is substantial. Cost-of-repair threshold rule of thumb: if the repair quote exceeds 50% of replacement cost AND the unit is over 10 years old, replacement usually wins. We tell you the math on the diagnostic visit before you authorize work."
  },
  {
    q: "Why is my Samsung dryer squeaking?",
    a: "Two common causes, easy to distinguish on diagnostic. (1) Idler pulley, the spring-loaded pulley that maintains tension on the drum belt. The bearing in the pulley wears, and the squeak is loudest at the start of every cycle and during tumble. Year 5-9 typical wear window. Replacement runs $195-$295 with the drum belt as a paired set (always replace the belt with the pulley, old belt + new pulley fails again within months). (2) Drum support rollers (front and rear bearings the drum rotates on), wear on these makes a deeper rumble or grinding rather than a high squeak, and shows up year 7-11. Replacement $245-$385 typical with both rollers. About 70% of squeaking-dryer calls trace to idler pulley; 25% to drum rollers; 5% to motor bearing. Diagnostic separates them in 10 minutes by listening through a stethoscope or by manually rotating the drum with the belt removed."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you carry Samsung dryer parts on the truck?",
    a: "Yes, Samsung dryers are among the brands we stock most heavily. Common items always on the truck: thermal fuses, cycling thermostats, thermistors, heating elements (electric, multiple sizes), drum belts, idler pulleys, drum support rollers, door switches, door latches, lint filter assemblies. Less common: drive motors, main control boards, gas valve coils (gas models), MultiSteam steam generator components, these come from authorized Samsung distribution, usually 1-3 day lead. We confirm the exact part needed against your model number on the diagnostic visit before quoting. About 80% of Samsung dryer repairs we run are completed same-day on the diagnostic visit because the parts are already on the truck."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you service Samsung dryers in Pasadena, Newport Beach, the Inland Empire, and other parts of SoCal?",
    a: "Yes, Samsung dryers are one of the most-installed dryer brands in our 5-county service area, and we service them from all 8 dispatch territories. The DV-WashTower vertical stacked unit is heavily concentrated in newer construction across Pasadena, Calabasas, Hidden Hills, and parts of the Inland Empire (Rancho Cucamonga, Temecula). Standard DV-series electric dryers are everywhere across the broader SoCal market. DVG gas dryers are common in homes built before the all-electric construction trend, especially across the San Fernando Valley and older Westside neighborhoods. The technician on your call comes from the closest branch with the Samsung dryer parts most likely to be needed already on the truck."
  }
